04908nam a2200649Ia 9780231554237DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315542377 a10.7312/russ201722doi  a(DE-B1597)665682  a(OCoLC)1356966255  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aQC903b.R865 2023 7aLAN0080002bisacsh04a070.4/4936373874223/eng/202301051 aRussell, Adrienne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Mediated Climate :bHow Journalists, Big Tech, and Activists Are Vying for Our Future /cAdrienne Russell. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Two Crises -- t1. House on Fire -- t2. Noise, Incivility, and Ambivalence -- t3. After Peak Indifference -- t4. Collective Imaginary -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTo what extent does journalism deserve blame for the failure to address climate change over the last thirty years? Critics point out that climate coverage has often lacked necessary urgency and hewed to traditional notions of objectivity and balance that allowed powerful interests—mainly fossil fuel companies—to manufacture doubt. Climate journalism, however, developed alongside the digital media landscape, which is characterized by rampant misinformation, political polarization, unaccountable tech companies, unchecked corporate power, and vast inequalities. Under these circumstances, journalism struggled, and bad actors flourished, muddling messages while emissions mounted and societies struggled to avert catastrophe.The Mediated Climate explores the places where the climate and information crises meet, examining how journalism, activism, corporations, and Big Tech compete to influence the public. Adrienne Russell argues that the inadequate response to climate change is intertwined with the profound challenges facing the communications environment. She demonstrates that the information crisis is driven not only by technological changes but also by concentrated power that predates the rise of digital media companies. Efforts to improve climate coverage must take into account the larger social and material contexts in which journalism operates and the broader power dynamics that shape public discourse. Drawing on interviews with journalists and activists, Russell considers the ways recent movements are battling misinformation. She offers timely recommendations to foster engagement with climate issues and calls on readers to join in efforts to reshape the media landscape to better serve the public interest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aClimatic changesxPress coverage. 0aDisinformation. 0aJournalistic ethics. 0aMass media and the environment. 0aMisinformation. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Journalism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Library and Information Science 2023 Englishz978311131915508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Library and Information Science 2023z9783111318233oZDB-23-DGB40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/russ2017240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231554237423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231554237/original  a978-3-11-074967-0  Columbia Universi